V[[Image:PSNovikov.jpg|200px|thumb|right|'''''P. S. Novikov'''''.]]\u000a'''Pyotr Sergeyevich Novikov''' ({{lang-ru|\u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0301\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041d\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432}}; 15 August 1901, [[Moscow]], [[Russian Empire]] \u2013 9 January 1975, Moscow, [[Soviet Union]]) was a [[USSR|Soviet]] [[mathematician]].\u000a\u000aNovikov is known for his work on combinatorial problems in [[group theory]]: the [[word problem for groups]], and [[Burnside's problem]]. For proving the [[undecidability]] of the word problem in groups he was awarded the [[Lenin Prize]] in 1957.<ref>S. I. Adian, ''Mathematical logic, the theory of algorithms and the theory of sets'', AMS Bookstore, 1977, ISBN 0-8218-3033-3, p. 26.</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 1953 he became a corresponding member of the [[USSR Academy of Sciences]] and in 1960 he was elected a full member.\u000a\u000aHe was married to the mathematician [[Lyudmila Keldysh]] (1904\u20131976). The mathematician [[Sergei Novikov (mathematician)|Sergei Novikov]] is his son. [[Sergei Adian]] and [[Albert Muchnik]] were among his students.\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a== External links ==\u000a\u000a* {{MacTutor|id=Novikov}}\u000a* {{MathGenealogy|id=55513}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Novikov, Pyotr}}\u000a[[Category:1901 births]]\u000a[[Category:1975 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:Russian mathematicians]]\u000a[[Category:Soviet mathematicians]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century mathematicians]]\u000a[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Soviet logicians]]\u000a[[Category:Group theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Full Members of the USSR Academy of Sciences]]\u000a\u000a\u000a{{Russia-mathematician-stub}}
